soc.message

Class SOCVersion

  • java.lang.Object
    • soc.message.SOCMessage
      • soc.message.SOCVersion
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, SOCMessageFromUnauthClient

    public class SOCVersion
extends SOCMessage
implements SOCMessageFromUnauthClient
    This message sends the server's version and features, or client's version and locale, to the other side of the connection. VERSION is the first message sent from client to server. The server sends its version to the client as its first outbound message, not in response to client's SOCVersion. Version numbers are read via Version.

    Before 2.0.00, the client did not send its locale or optional features (SOCFeatureSet). If locale not sent by client, server should probably assume en_US since older versions had all messages in english. For robots the locale field is ignored at server, because bots don't parse server text messages; sending a SOCImARobot message will clear the robot client's locale to null at the server.

    Before 1.1.19, the server did not send its active optional features; new clients of older servers should use the SOCFeatureSet(true, true) constructor to set the default features active.

    Before 1.1.06, in SOCPlayerClient, this was sent first from server to client, then client responded. Robot clients have always sent first since the introduction in 1.1.00 of client-server versioning (2008-08-07).

    Since:
    1.1.00
    Author:
    Jeremy D Monin <jeremy@nand.net>

           throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Create a Version message.
        Parameters:
        verNum - The version number, as in Version.versionNumber()
        verStr - The version display string, as in Version.version()
        verBuild - The version build, or null, as in Version.buildnum()
        feats - The server's or client's active optional features, or null, as in SOCFeatureSet.getEncodedList(). Not sent by servers older than 1.1.19 or clients older than 2.0.00; see SOCFeatureSet.SOCFeatureSet(boolean, boolean) for default features at older versions. Server can send this to a client older than 1.1.19, it is safely ignored.
        cliLocale - The client's JVM locale, or null, as in Locale.toString(); not sent by servers or by clients older than 2.0.00.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if verBuild is null and feats != null; not supported by message encoding to clients older than 2.0.00.

      • toCmd

        public static java.lang.String toCmd(int verNum,
                                     java.lang.String verStr,
                                     java.lang.String verBuild,
                                     java.lang.String feats,
                                     java.lang.String cliLocale)
                              throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        VERSION SEP vernum SEP2 verstr [SEP2 build [SEP2 feats [SEP2 cliLocale]]]. Build, feats, and cliLocale are optional and may be blank (SOCMessage.EMPTYSTR).

        Empty strings should not be given as parameters; use null instead for optional fields.

        Parameters:
        verNum - the version number, like 1100 for 1.1.00, as in Version.versionNumber(); not null
        verStr - the version as string, like "1.1.00"; not null
        verBuild - the version build, or null, from Version.buildnum()
        feats - The server's or client's active optional features, or null, as in SOCFeatureSet.getEncodedList(). Not sent by servers older than 1.1.19 or clients older than 2.0.00; see SOCFeatureSet.SOCFeatureSet(boolean, boolean) for default features at older versions. Server can send this to a client older than 1.1.19, it is safely ignored.
        cliLocale - The client's JVM locale, or null, as in Locale.toString(). Not sent by servers or by clients older than 2.0.00.
        Returns:
        the command string
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if verBuild is null and feats != null; not supported by message encoding to clients older than 2.0.00.

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Get a delimited human-readable form of this message. Null fields are rendered as "=(null)", which is unambiguous because of the restricted format of those fields; the string "(null)" wouldn't be valid contents.

        Before v2.4.50, fields were comma-separated; that version changed to use standard '|' separator.
